@@eSepulchur Pasture: Where Midgaard Monetized Grief@@N

@@yFrom the Garden Ledger, Moral Accounting Archive@@N
@@dRead aloud annually at the Bloom Pavilion Remembrance@@N

South of Midgaard's gates lies the field where the city proved
what Elys Savan always feared: that a civilization built on ledgers
will eventually @@rledger its dead@@N.

The @@dNinth Acre@@N was once a place where shepherd-priests rang a
bell at dusk to guide the lost. That bell was a @@gpromise@@N --
someone listening, someone caring, without filing a report or
entering the act into a civic register.

Then Midgaard @@yimproved@@N it. Road dead routed to the acre. Names
copied from signet rings. Effects cataloged. Graves marked by
category. During the @@rAsh-and-Iron Decades@@N, Midgaard imposed
the @@yTithe of Last Burdens@@N: a burial tariff. Families who
could @@ypay@@N bought sanctified plots. Those who could not were
entered as @@d"deferred names"@@N -- interred in common furrows
pending claim.

@@dDeferred names.@@N The Garden Ledger Clerks cannot write those
words without trembling. People reduced to accounting entries.
The dead transformed from @@gbeloved@@N into @@rreceivable@@N. As
though a mother's grief required a @@yfiling deadline@@N.

A quiet industry formed: clerks charging for corrections, carriers
misplacing evidence, wardens delaying remains, brokers trading
inheritance rumor. The Bloom Pavilion calls this the @@rultimate
indictment of ledger culture@@N -- corruption grown @@rin the space
between the living and their dead@@N.

When the @@WViolet Compact's@@N containment doctrine spread, certain
remains were forbidden burial. Holding pens, wardwire trenches,
witness lantern circles. The Compact called it safety. Temple
mourners called it trapping souls in legal limbo.

Then the @@rgravebell rang twice for every pull@@N. Names recorded
without bodies. Bodies interred without names. The ledger had
@@rfailed@@N, and the dead began their own accounting.

Children still repeat at dusk: @@d"Pay the living, name the dead,
and do not let the bell count twice."@@N

In Rakuen, we bury our dead in the orchards. Elys Savan wrote:
@@g"The dead nourish what the living tend, and the living tend
what the dead loved."@@N No tariff. No deferred names. A @@gflower@@N
planted above, a @@yname@@N spoken aloud, and that is @@genough@@N.

The Cracked Promise Stones facing Sepulchur Pasture bear a carving
added after the second petition was refused: @@d"They will count
the dead before they count us among the living."@@N
